✅ One query that’s usually fast even without indexes
(Uses a temp table inside the script — still “one thing to paste/run”)
/* 1) Pull the ER claims you care about into a small temp table */
IF OBJECT_ID('tempdb..#er') IS NOT NULL DROP TABLE #er;

SELECT TOP (5000)
    ev.GMPI_ID,
    CAST(ev.ER_DATE AS date) AS ER_DATE,
    ev.CLAIM_ID_ER,
    ev.HOSPITAL_PROVIDER,
    ev.ER_STATUS,
    ev.ER_CATEGORY
INTO #er
FROM BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.FACT_ER_VISITS ev
WHERE ev.ER_STATUS = 'TRUE ER'
  AND ev.ER_DATE >= DATEADD(day, -10, CAST(GETDATE() AS date))
ORDER BY ev.ER_DATE DESC;

/* 2) Pull ONLY procedure rows for those ER claims, rank them, pick best one */
WITH proc_ranked AS (
    SELECT
        fcp.CLAIM_ID,
        fcp.CODE      AS PROCEDURE_CODE,
        fcp.CODE_NAME,
        ROW_NUMBER() OVER (
            PARTITION BY fcp.CLAIM_ID
            ORDER BY
                CASE
                    WHEN fcp.CODE IN ('99281','99282','99283','99284','99285',
                                     'G0380','G0381','G0382','G0383','G0384') THEN 1
                    WHEN fcp.CODE >= '0450' AND fcp.CODE <= '0459' THEN 2
                    ELSE 3
                END,
                fcp.SERVICE_FROM_DATE DESC,
                fcp.SERVICE_LINE DESC
        ) AS rn
    FROM BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE fcp
    JOIN #er e
        ON e.CLAIM_ID_ER = fcp.CLAIM_ID
)
SELECT
    dm.GMPI_ID,
    dm.MEMBER_MBI,
    dm.MEMBER_FIRST_NAME,
    dm.MEMBER_LAST_NAME,
    dm.MEMBER_DATE_OF_BIRTH,

    e.ER_DATE,
    e.HOSPITAL_PROVIDER,
    e.ER_STATUS,
    e.ER_CATEGORY,
    e.CLAIM_ID_ER,

    p.PROCEDURE_CODE,
    p.CODE_NAME
FROM #er e
LEFT JOIN BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.dim_member dm
    ON dm.GMPI_ID = e.GMPI_ID
LEFT JOIN proc_ranked p
    ON p.CLAIM_ID = e.CLAIM_ID_ER
   AND p.rn = 1
ORDER BY e.ER_DATE DESC;
Why this is faster

It first creates #er with only 5000 ER claims

Then it joins FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE to only those 5000 claim IDs

That prevents a full scan of the entire procedure table

If this is still slow, then FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE is almost certainly:

a view, or

extremely large with no usable indexes, or

blocked by resource limits

✅ If you need it even faster for testing

Change these two numbers:

TOP (5000) → TOP (200)

-10 days → -3 days

That should return almost instantly.

2 quick checks that explain “why everything is slow”

Run these (they’re fast):

Check 1: Is it a table or a view?
SELECT
    o.type_desc,
    s.name AS schema_name,
    o.name AS object_name
FROM sys.objects o
JOIN sys.schemas s ON s.schema_id = o.schema_id
WHERE s.name = 'dbo'
  AND o.name = 'FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE';

If type_desc = VIEW, that’s a huge clue.

Check 2: Does it have an index on CLAIM_ID?
SELECT
    i.name AS index_name,
    c.name AS column_name
FROM sys.indexes i
JOIN sys.index_columns ic
  ON i.object_id = ic.object_id AND i.index_id = ic.index_id
JOIN sys.columns c
  ON ic.object_id = c.object_id AND ic.column_id = c.column_id
WHERE i.object_id = OBJECT_ID('BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE')
  AND c.name IN ('CLAIM_ID');

If this returns nothing → there’s no index on CLAIM_ID.

What you can do right now (practical)

Run the temp table script above with TOP (200) and -3 days

If still slow, run the “table vs view” query — that will explain it immediately

If it’s a view / no index, you can tell your team:

Joining FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE is slow because the object appears to be (a VIEW / not indexed on CLAIM_ID). For now I can deliver the SMS output reliably from FACT_ER_VISITS + dim_member, and we can add procedure code later if we materialize/index a smaller procedure subset.
